description: The Ewha Womans University Museum was built in 1935. The original name of Ewha Womans University was Ewha College, and it was renamed Ewha Womans University in 1948. The university was built to preserve the country's cultural heritage under the rule of Japanese imperialism. The collections in the museum are mainly folk items, woodwork products, ceramics, etc. collected by professors and students at that time. Visitors are not allowed to enter the buildings in Ewha Womans University, only this museum is allowed to enter.

address: 22-5 Sinchonnyeok-ro, Daehyeon-dong, Seodaemun-gu, Seoul, South Korea

description: The Buk Seoul Museum of Art has 6 floors, divided into 3 floors above ground and 3 floors below ground. There are several galleries such as photo galleries and children's galleries in the museum. There are also art shops, cafes, restaurants, children's rooms, nursing rooms and other convenient facilities in the museum, which are very suitable for bringing children to play. In addition, tourists can visit the wild wisteria cultural park here, which has sculptures and sculptures full of personality.

address: South Korea, Gyeonggi-do, Yangju-si, Jangheung-myeon, Gwonnyul-ro, 193 KR
